 virtual reality. In this book, J. B. Kuipers introduces quaternions for scientists and engineers who have not encountered them before and shows how they can be used in a variety of practical situations. The book is primarily an exposition of the quaternion, a 4-tuple, and its primary application in a rotation operator. But Kuipers also presents the more conventional and familiar 3 x 3 (9-element) matrix rotation operator. These parallel presentations allow the reader to judge which approaches are preferable for specific applications. The volume is divided into three main parts. The opening chapters present introductory material and establish the book's terminology and notation. The next part presents the mathematical properties of quaternions, including quaternion algebra and geometry. It includes more advanced special topics in spherical trigonometry, along with an introduction to quaternion calculus and perturbation theory, required in many situations involving dynamics and kinematics. In the final section, Kuipers discusses state-of-the-art applications. He presents a six degree-of-freedom electromagnetic position and orientation transducer and concludes by discussing the computer graphics necessary for the development of applications in virtual reality.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aQuaternions. 7aMATHEMATICS / Applied.2bisacsh  aEuler angle.  aaircraft.  aalgorithm.  aangles.  acomplex numbers.  acoordinate frame.  acoupling.  adirection cosine.  aelectromagnetic.  afactor.  ageometry.  agreat-circle.  ahomogeneous coordinates.  aidentity.  aincremental rotation.  ainverse.  amatrix.  anumber.  aorientation.  aperspective.  aphase plane.  aprojection.  aquaternion.  arotation.  aseasons.  aspherical.  atrace of a matrix.  avirtual reality.08iTitle is p